Documents the Neovim-side consumer of the steno-ts theory: a plugin that watches inserted text for `@@token@@` markers (produced when Plover types a stroke's mapped token) and expands them into real LSP snippets with tabstops via `vim.snippet.expand`, replacing the `{#Up}{#Left}` cursor-hack style used by Plover's own `plain`/`smart` dictionaries.

Two generated artifacts are load-bearing and come from the same compiler command (`cargo run --bin build-nvim`), so they must be regenerated together and stay paired: `out/plover-keys.json` (stroke → `@@token@@`, loaded into Plover as a dictionary) and `out/snippets.json` (`@@token@@` → LSP snippet body, loaded by this plugin). If the token format or set drifts between the two, tokens typed by Plover won't match what the plugin expects.

Setup is via `require("steno-ts").setup({ snippets_path = ..., filetypes = {...} })`; requires Neovim 0.10+ for built-in `vim.snippet`. The plugin attaches a `TextChangedI` autocmd on configured filetypes and expands only when a *complete* `@@token@@` sits at the cursor — partial tokens are left alone until the closing `@@` appears.

Known unresolved edge case (not yet fixed, documented as a caveat rather than a bug to silently work around): single/fused-stroke outlines expand cleanly, but chained type-appends through a non-terminal head (e.g. `Promise` → `Promise<string>`) can leave stray characters, because Plover's retro-delete-on-next-stroke counts the length of the *token* it originally typed, not the expanded snippet text that replaced it. Non-terminal "pre-function" partials are intentionally present in `snippets.json`; the caveat is about runtime chaining behavior, not about removing those entries.